                <p>[Omitted here is discussion unrelated to the International Sugar Agreement.]</p>
                <pb facs="0779" n="734" xml:id="pg_734"/>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">International Sugar Agreement</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_USTR_1">USTR</gloss> Deputy Director <persName
                        corresp="#p_SMB_1">Smith</persName> reported to the <gloss target="#t_SIG_1"
                        >SIG</gloss> that the United States needs to decide whether we should
                    participate in the forthcoming meetings on an International Sugar Agreement.
                        <gloss target="#t_USTR_1">USTR</gloss> and State strongly urged
                    participation noting that while we are generally not favorably disposed to
                    commodity agreements (e.g., <gloss target="#t_SIGIEP_1">SIG–IEP</gloss>
                    conclusions on coffee agreement),<note n="2" xml:id="d295fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d290">Document 290</ref>.</note> we have little to lose from
                    entering into these discussions.<note n="3" xml:id="d295fn3">In an April 28
                        action memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_WWA_1">Wallis</persName>
                        recommending his approval of formal <gloss target="#t_US_1">U.S.</gloss>
                        participation in negotiations for a new <gloss target="#t_ISA_1"
                        >ISA</gloss>, <persName corresp="#p_MCRT_1">McCormack</persName> explained
                        that <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">Shultz</persName> had “consented to permit
                        U.S. Government representatives to attend the negotiations on the new <gloss
                            target="#t_ISA_1">ISA</gloss>, while reserving the right not to sign any
                        subsequent agreement should the agreement not meet our minimum
                        requirements.” (Department of State, Files of the Under Secretary of State
                        for Economic Affairs, <persName corresp="#p_WWA_1">W. Allen
                            Wallis</persName>, Chrons; Memo to the Secretary/Staff and
                        Departmental/Other Agencies; Memos to the Files; White House Correspondence,
                        1987–1987, Lot 89D378: Memos—Staff/Departmental 1982–1985) <persName
                            corresp="#p_WWA_1">Wallis</persName> approved <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                            >U.S.</gloss> participation in negotiations for a new <gloss
                            target="#t_ISA_1">ISA</gloss>, subject to “certain understandings” about
                        the interpretation of the negotiating instructions for the delegation
                        outlined in an undated covering memorandum. (Ibid.)</note> By not
                    participating, we give it higher visibility than if we do participate.
                    Furthermore, the <gloss target="#t_EC_1">EC</gloss> is the real culprit, and
                    some of the criticism toward the <gloss target="#t_EC_1">EC</gloss>’s common
                    agricultural policy might be blunted if the United States were to become the
                    scapegoat by not taking part. State also noted that these negotiations are
                    viewed as very important by our Latin American friends. The <gloss
                        target="#t_SIGIEP_1">SIG–IEP</gloss> concurred with the views of State and
                        <gloss target="#t_USTR_1">USTR</gloss>, but the Chairman did note that our
                    general views on the undesirability of commodity agreements still holds.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of the Polish debt situation.]</p>
